The correct answer is B. pyroclastic flow.  

The eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79 A.D. produced a deadly pyroclastic flow—a fast-moving current of hot gas and volcanic matter—that overwhelmed Pompeii and Herculaneum. While lava and gases were present, the primary cause of death was the intense heat and suffocation from the pyroclastic surge.  

